eld, criticism from the outside is essential. We may not be able to be sufficiently self-critical on our own, but trusted criticism from outside, even if resisted, can begin to change our perspective-at which point transformative self-criticism becomes a real option.   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 22. Okt 2019) 0aAmbiguity in science. 0aMathematicszEnglandxHistoryy19th century. 0aSciencexHistoryy19th century. 0aSciencexPhilosophy. 4aCritical Rationalism. 4aFramework-Dependenc. 4aThomas Kuhn. 4aambivalence. 4acreatively undecided. 4anormative commitment. 4anormative criticism. 4aself criticism. 4atrusted critics. 70(DE-601)1057472970(DE-588)4124501-5aZweifel2gnd 70(DE-601)1057974990(DE-588)4117665-0aWissenschaftstheorie2gnd 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018z978311063537940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226514659423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/doc/cover/9780226514659.jpg  a978-3-11-063537-9  University of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles